3. Transaction Management:
  What is Transaction? Group of DB operations that must be atomic ✔ All succeed OR all fail
      🔧 Without Spring (Manual)
      con.setAutoCommit(false);
      try {
          // operations
          con.commit();
      } catch(Exception e) {
          con.rollback();
      }
      ✅ With Spring
      @Transactional
      public void transfer() {
          debit();
          credit();
      }
  How @Transactional Works
   Uses: AOP (proxy-based) and Intercepts method
   Flow: Method call → Proxy → Begin transaction →Execute method → Commit / Rollback
   
  In the Spring Framework, @Transactional mainly does:
        👉 Transaction management
        👉 AND also binds a Hibernate Session to that transaction
   Key Concept: Session is tied to the transaction lifecycle
   Internal Flow : Method call → Spring AOP Proxy → Start Transaction → Create / Fetch Session → 
                   Bind Session to current thread →Execute method →Commit / Rollback → Close Session
   Who manages the Session?
  👉 Spring uses: HibernateTransactionManager (Hibernate) and JpaTransactionManager (JPA)
                  ✔ These manage both: Transaction and Session / EntityManager

    @Transactional
    public void saveUser() {
        repository.save(user);
    }
     What happens internally:
          Transaction starts
          Session is created (or reused)
          Session is bound to thread (ThreadLocal)
          Repository uses same session
          Commit → session flushed → closed
  
  Important Concept: “Session per Transaction”
    👉 Spring follows: ONE Transaction → ONE Session
    🔥 Why this is important?
          Ensures consistency
          Enables: Lazy loading and Dirty checking
    ⚠️ Without @Transactional
    public void saveUser() {
        repository.save(user);
    } 
    ❌ Problems: Session may not be properly managed, LazyInitializationException and No rollback

  Why LazyInitializationException Happens- Exception thrown when lazy-loaded data is accessed without an active session
   Root Cause-  Lazy data needs: Active Session (Persistence Context)
  ❌ Case 1: Without @Transactional
          public User getUser() {
              return repo.findById(1).get();
          }
          Later: user.getOrders(); // ❌ Exception
          Why? Method ends → Session closed → Lazy data accessed → Exception
  ❌ Case 2: Even WITH @Transactional
          @Transactional
          public User getUser() {
              return repo.findById(1).get();
          }
          Then:
            User user = service.getUser();
            user.getOrders(); // ❌ Exception
           Why?  @Transactional ends → Session closed → Lazy access outside method
     @Transactional only works inside method boundary
  How to Fix
  ✔ Option 1: Access inside transaction
            @Transactional
            public User getUser() {
                User user = repo.findById(1).get();
                user.getOrders().size(); // initialize
                return user;
            }
  ✔ Option 2: Use JOIN FETCH - @Query("SELECT u FROM User u JOIN FETCH u.orders")
  ✔ Option 3: DTO projection
  ✔ Option 4: Open Session in View (OSIV) ✔ Keeps session open till view
              👉 Even without @Transactional: ✔ Spring Boot may keep session open till view layer. Controller → Service → View
              ⚠️ But: Not recommended for heavy apps Can cause performance issues
  
  Transaction Propagation -  Defines how transactions behave when methods call each other
        Syntax
        @Transactional(propagation = Propagation.REQUIRED)
    Types
  🔹 REQUIRED (Default) -If transaction exists → use it  Else → create new
  🔹 REQUIRES_NEW - Always create new transaction  and Suspend existing one
  🔹 SUPPORTS - Use existing if present  Else → run without transaction
  🔹 NOT_SUPPORTED - Run without transaction  Suspend existing
  🔹 MANDATORY- Must have transaction  Else → exception
  🔹 NEVER - Must NOT have transaction  Else → exception
  🔹 NESTED - Uses savepoints (partial rollback)
  
  Isolation Levels (Data Consistency) - Defines how transactions see data
     Syntax
          @Transactional(isolation = Isolation.READ_COMMITTED)
     Levels
  🔹 READ_UNCOMMITTED - Dirty reads allowed
  🔹 READ_COMMITTED (Default) -No dirty reads
  🔹 REPEATABLE_READ -Same data on repeated reads
  🔹 SERIALIZABLE -Strictest (like single-thread)

    How Rollback Works in @Transactional
    Default Behavior: Rollback ONLY on RuntimeException
          @Transactional
          public void transfer() {
              debit();
              credit(); // throws RuntimeException
          }
     Entire transaction rolled back
     
    Checked Exception Case - throw new Exception(); 👉 ❌ NO rollback by default
     ✅ Fix - @Transactional(rollbackFor = Exception.class)
     Internal Working
    Method call →Spring Proxy →Start transaction →Execute method →If exception: rollback Else: commit


